p: Tedaniophorbasins A ( 1) and B ( 2) were tested for their ability to inhibit the growth of chloroquine-sensitive (3D7) and chloroquine-resistant (Dd2) strains of the malaria parasite Plasmodium falciparum [ 21], inhibition of the growth of the trypanosome Trypanosoma brucei brucei [ 22], and cytotoxicity towards pancreatic (Bx-PC-3, Panc-1, and Su-86-86) and breast cancer (BT-474, MCF-10A, and MDA-MB-231) cell lines [ 23] (assays that we routinely run in our labs), however, both compounds were inactive against all targets at the highest concentration (40 ÂµM) tested.
